  "prompt": "Why is sodium hydrogen carbonate soluble in water?",
  "response": "Sodium hydrogen carbonate (NaHCO3), also known as sodium bicarbonate or baking soda, is soluble in water due to several key factors:\n\n1. Ionic compound\n- NaHCO3 is an ionic compound composed of sodium (Na+) and hydrogen carbonate (HCO3-) ions\n- Ionic compounds generally have high water solubility\n\n2. Polar water molecules\n- Water molecules are polar, with a slightly positive hydrogen end and a slightly negative oxygen end\n- These polar water molecules can interact with and surround the sodium and hydrogen carbonate ions\n\n3. Ion-dipole interactions\n- Water molecules form hydration shells around the ions\n- Sodium ions (Na+) are surrounded by the oxygen end of water molecules\n- Hydrogen carbonate ions (HCO3-) are surrounded by the hydrogen end of water molecules\n\n4. Breaking ionic bonds\n- Water molecules can overcome the electrostatic attractions between sodium and hydrogen carbonate ions\n- This process allows the ions to separate and distribute throughout the water\n\n5. Entropy increase\n- Dissolving creates more disorder in the system, which is thermodynamically favorable\n\nThese factors contribute to sodium hydrogen carbonate's relatively high solubility in water, with approximately 96 g dissolving per liter of water at room temperature.",
